    en: {
      title: 'Echoes of Moosburg',
      windowTitle: 'Echoes_Moosburg.html — service design, not app build ✦',
      description: "Hybrid service-design ecosystem for Moosburg's history: physical signs, mobile web app and partner institutions — tested across three generations.",
      heroImage: 'assets/Portfolio_Content/Echoes_of_Moosburg/Screenshot_20260116_184348 1.png',
      keyInsight: "\"We're not building an app. We're building a living network.\" — Moosburg's history doesn't belong in the archive, it belongs in everyday life. Partners aren't users — they're co-creators.",
      tldr: {
        problem: "Moosburg's history is invisible in everyday life — fragmented info, generational rift, app aversion.",
        myRole: 'UX research (6 interviews, city walks), service & ecosystem design, stakeholder coordination, hi-fi prototype.',
        solution: 'Hybrid ecosystem: signs + web app + partners (schools, adult-ed, cafés, STALAG VII A e.V.).',
        outcome: 'Tested across 3 generations. 3 hardware variants, 2 content partners. Direct-entry shipped after testing.',
      },
      problemShort: "The silent city memory: Moosburg's history is invisible in everyday life, information fragmented, generational rift looming.",
      solutionShort: 'Hybrid service-design ecosystem: physical signs + mobile web app + partner institutions (schools, adult-ed, cafés, associations).',
      role: 'UX Research, Service & Ecosystem Design, Stakeholder Coordination, Prototyping',
      duration: 'Winter 2024/25 (3 months, delivery 18.01.2026)',
      team: 'Team B',
      tools: ['Figma', 'Miro', 'Canva', 'HTML/CSS/JS'],
      roleChips: ['🔍 Research', '🗂️ Service Design', '🌐 Ecosystem', '✏️ Prototyping'],

      /* ── Problem ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
      problemStatement: "Moosburg's silent memory — a town with STALAG VII A, medieval fabric, hundreds of stories — and none of it is visible in daily life.",
      problemContext: "Anyone curious about Moosburg's history lands in fragmented sources: city website, adult-ed course list, the Stalag association, museum, walking tours — each its own island. Nobody knows where to start. Three problems stack: (1) Web dilemma — information scattered across 5+ sources. (2) Pull vs. push — people have to actively search, in the moment of curiosity there's nothing to grab. (3) App fatigue + craving for the physical — users don't want an app, but they want physical anchors and trust. And on top: a generational rift — older people still know the stories, younger ones don't even know stories exist.",
      problemImage: '',

      /* ── Research ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
      researchContext: 'Six qualitative interviews across three generations (18–72 yrs), two city walks at historical sites, empathy mapping per persona, a customer journey from "discover" to "share". Plus stakeholder conversations with STALAG VII A e.V. and Karl Bauer (local historian) — both later became content partners, not just sources.',
      researchImage: '',
      research: [
        '6 qualitative interviews (18–72 yrs) — tourist · resident · student · senior',
        'City walks at historical sites — where do people look, where do they walk past?',
        'Empathy mapping per persona — Says / Thinks / Feels / Does',
        'Customer journey: discover → understand → share with others',
        'Stakeholder conversations with STALAG VII A e.V. and Karl Bauer (local historian)',
      ],
      insights: [
        'Web dilemma: information fragmented across 5+ sources. Nobody knows where to start.',
        "Pull vs. push: at the moment of curiosity, information isn't there. People give up.",
        'App fatigue: nobody installs an app for a one-time experience. But signs and brochures get picked up.',
        "Generational rift: older people know the stories, younger ones don't even know stories exist.",
        "Tradition and modernity don't have to clash — the rose from the older coat of arms becomes the visual bridge.",
      ],
      hmw: [
        "How might we bring history out of archives and into daily life — without an app download?",
        'How might we link places to knowledge without building new infrastructure?',
        'How might we turn institutions (schools, adult-ed, cafés) into co-creators, not just users?',
      ],

      /* ── Solution ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
      solutionStatement: "Not: an app. But: a living network of physical anchors, digital depth, and partner institutions making history alive together.",
      solutionContext: 'Three pillars: (1) Physical touchpoints — a central info-stele at Marienplatz with QR + brochure rack, themed signs at the STALAG site, info-posts that upgrade existing signage, QR codes on benches and café tables (guerrilla tactic). (2) Digital depth — a mobile web app (no download): time-travel slider (then/now overlaid), audio diaries of real STALAG voices, central hub linking ALL city resources (adult-ed courses, association tours, museum, school programmes), a community guestbook for citizen stories. (3) Ecosystem partners — schools teach on-site, adult-ed promotes courses directly in the app, cafés offer the QR codes as a feature, STALAG VII A e.V. provides authentic content. Every partner wins — and the city gets a living memory culture. Visual thread: the rose from the older Moosburg coat of arms — on the stele it guards the QR code, on the welcome screen it greets the user. Brand palette: parchment beige (#EDE4D5), rust red (#D24638), moss green (#0B3E33).',
      solutionImage: '',
      concept: 'Three pillars working together — physical anchors (3 sign types + brochures + guerrilla QR), digital depth (web app with time-travel slider, audio diaries, central hub, community guestbook) and partner institutions (schools, adult-ed, cafés, STALAG VII A e.V.). No pillar works in isolation — and that is the point.',
      beforeImage: '',
      afterImage: '',
      designScreens: [
        {
          name: 'Info-stele at Marienplatz',
          description: 'Central anchor: info panel, QR code (rose guards it), brochure rack — adult-ed courses, walking tours and museum flyers come out of the buildings and onto the street.',
          image: '',
        },
        {
          name: 'Themed signs at STALAG site',
          description: 'Compact, personal, emotional. Single diary excerpts, a "then" photo over a "today" view, QR code for the full audio story in the app.',
          image: '',
        },
        {
          name: 'Web app: time-travel slider',
          description: 'A 1945 photo over today\'s view — slide interactively across. "Oh, that\'s why this looks like this." Visual transformation, not a fact sheet.',
          image: '',
        },
        {
          name: 'Web app: central hub',
          description: 'Solves the web dilemma: adult-ed courses, association tours, museum, school programmes, community stories — all city resources in one place, one logic.',
          image: '',
        },
      ],

      /* ── Results ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
      outcome: 'Hybrid service-design system, tested across three generations with 5 usability tests. Three hardware variants (central stele, themed signs, info-post upgrade module) and a mobile web app with time-travel slider, audio diaries and central hub. Credibility via two content partners (STALAG VII A e.V., Karl Bauer). Complete brand identity with the Moosburg rose as a cross-generational visual thread. Most important testing insight implemented: direct entry after QR-scan instead of a welcome screen — time-to-content is critical.',
      resultsImage: '',
      learnings: [
        'Service design > product design. An app alone would not have solved the problem — schools, adult-ed, associations and cafés had to be part of the solution, not just stakeholders.',
        'Hybrid beats either/or. Not digital OR physical — signs build trust, the app delivers depth, brochures get picked up and taken home.',
        'Time-to-content is critical. After a QR-scan, users expect experience immediately, not explanation. Welcome screens out, direct entry in.',
        'Partners need their own benefit. Schools want vivid teaching, adult-ed wants visibility, cafés want a feature. When everyone wins, the system runs without a top-down push.',
      ],
      wouldChange: [
        "Embed the research in the partners' existing rituals — STALAG VII A e.V. talks to visitors every day. I arrived with a finished interview guide instead of walking a few of their tours and listening there. That would have produced more authentic quotes.",
        'Ditch the welcome screen earlier. The "time-to-content is critical" insight came in the second-to-last round of tests — three rounds before that, users had already bounced. I should have been testing direct entry from prototype v2 onwards.',
        'Prototype hardware variants in real materials, not just on paper. The debate about stele material (wood vs. concrete vs. metal) stayed too abstract — a simple 3D-printed mockup would have grounded partner conversations and maintenance questions.',
        "Bring schools in as research partners, not just solution-phase partners. Teachers see the generational rift up close every day — they would have delivered insights I needed 6 interviews to surface.",
        'Sell the ecosystem framing to the team earlier. For the first weeks we were still thinking "app", only in week 4 did it flip to "network". If we\'d established the framing at the start, the first two iterations wouldn\'t have been app-centric.',
      ],

      /* ── Reflection ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
      reflection: "Working with STALAG VII A e.V. taught me: UX research happens informally inside associations all the time — they talk to their visitors every day. Next project I'd embed research into the partners' existing rituals, instead of arriving with a finished interview guide. The biggest lesson: in service-design projects, partner institutions aren't users — they're co-creators. The app was the easy part — designing the system to stay alive was the actual design work.",

      /* ── Existing meta + media ─────────────────────────────────────── */
      metrics: [
        { l: 'Generations tested', v: '3' },
        { l: 'Usability tests', v: '5' },
        { l: 'Hardware variants', v: '3' },
        { l: 'Content partners', v: '2' },
      ],
      media: [
