        '"App-sprawl": citizens constantly switch between MVGO, München Parking, muenchen.de — no single source of truth.',
        'Important deadlines and appointments get lost — reminders arrive too late or not at all.',
        'Privacy concerns block adoption. Transparency is not a feature, it is a precondition.',
        'Accessibility is underestimated: seniors struggle with small text and unclear icons.',
        'Language barrier for tourists & newcomers — most services are German-only.',
      ],
      hmw: [
        'How might we integrate city services so citizens can plan their day in one app — no app-switching?',
        'How might we build trust in a centralised city app despite the sensitivity of the data?',
        'How might we make the app equally usable for 4 very different personas?',
      ],
      concept: 'A Munich Super App with a central dashboard for four service verticals: mobility (MVG · HandyParken), administration (city offices · applications), culture & leisure (Munich Ticket · museums · pools) and housing. Personalised, proactive reminders. Wallet and calendar integration. Accessibility as default — not as opt-in.',
      outcome: 'Complete service-design documentation: empathy maps, journey map, pains/gains synthesis, JTBD statements, personas. Plus a low-fi MIT App Inventor prototype and hi-fi Figma mockups. Implementation roadmap as a handover.',
      learnings: [
        'Four very different personas force real inclusivity — not lip service.',
        'Service design ≠ app design. The biggest problem was org and data architecture, not UI.',
        'A clean interview setup (consent, GDPR, anonymisation) makes participants more honest, not more cautious.',
        '"Small steps, shared synthesis" worked better in a 4-person team than siloed division of labour.',
      ],
      wouldChange: [
        'Next team project: write interview-guide v0 in week 1, not weeks 2-3 — we drifted apart for a bit before we synced up.',
        'Plan stakeholder interviews (MVG, city administration) in parallel with user research — service design needs both perspectives, we only had the citizen side.',
        'Establish "small steps, shared synthesis" as the team rhythm from day one — we only got into that rhythm mid-semester, before that too much silo work.',
      ],
      metrics: [{l:'Interviews', v:'6+'},{l:'Personas', v:'4'},{l:'Services integrated', v:'7'}],
